Import the crude oil price data and see visulaaize the data and check for Auto correlation and Partial autocorrelation

### Check whether the crudeoil price time series is staionary using ADF test and also check for MA and AR using ACF and PACF plots

ggAcf(CrudeOilplt)

ggPacf(CrudeOilplt)

adf.test(CrudeOilplt, alternative = "stationary")
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  CrudeOilplt
## Dickey-Fuller = -2.2586, Lag order = 7, p-value = 0.4679
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

From ADF test we saw that the crude oil price is not stationary. So we are differencing it to make it staionary

ggAcf(diff(CrudeOilplt))

ggPacf(diff(CrudeOilplt))

adf.test(diff(CrudeOilplt), alternative = "stationary")
## Warning in adf.test(diff(CrudeOilplt), alternative = "stationary"): p-value
## smaller than printed p-value
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  diff(CrudeOilplt)
## Dickey-Fuller = -7.7879, Lag order = 7, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary

From ACF , PACF and ADF test we know that Crude Oil price is not stationary and it has both the component of AR and MA. So we will use Auto arima to decide the best AR and MA levels for the Crudeoil Price

auto.arima(CrudeOilplt)
## Series: CrudeOilplt 
## ARIMA(2,1,2)(0,0,2)[12] 
## 
## Coefficients:
##          ar1      ar2      ma1     ma2    sma1     sma2
##       1.5021  -0.6024  -1.1356  0.2255  0.0866  -0.1525
## s.e.  0.0984   0.0945   0.1202  0.1148  0.0569   0.0533
## 
## sigma^2 estimated as 0.008891:  log likelihood=360.63
## AIC=-707.26   AICc=-706.96   BIC=-679.68

now fit the ARIMA model

fit<- Arima(CrudeOilplt, order=c(2,1,2), seasonal=c(0,0,2))
summary(fit)
## Series: CrudeOilplt 
## ARIMA(2,1,2)(0,0,2)[12] 
## 
## Coefficients:
##          ar1      ar2      ma1     ma2    sma1     sma2
##       1.5021  -0.6024  -1.1356  0.2255  0.0866  -0.1525
## s.e.  0.0984   0.0945   0.1202  0.1148  0.0569   0.0533
## 
## sigma^2 estimated as 0.008891:  log likelihood=360.63
## AIC=-707.26   AICc=-706.96   BIC=-679.68
## 
## Training set error measures:
##                       ME       RMSE        MAE        MPE     MAPE
## Training set 0.003056948 0.09342333 0.06542143 0.05207874 6.350123
##                   MASE         ACF1
## Training set 0.2361078 0.0005268406

Check whether residual is stationary

ggAcf(residuals(fit)) 

ggPacf(residuals(fit)) 

adf.test(residuals(fit), alternative = "stationary")
## Warning in adf.test(residuals(fit), alternative = "stationary"): p-value
## smaller than printed p-value
## 
##  Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test
## 
## data:  residuals(fit)
## Dickey-Fuller = -6.8581, Lag order = 7, p-value = 0.01
## alternative hypothesis: stationary
resid<-residuals(fit)
Box.test(resid, lag=12, type = "Ljung-Box", fitdf=1)
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  resid
## X-squared = 6.1741, df = 11, p-value = 0.8615
Box.test(resid, lag=24, type = "Ljung-Box", fitdf=1)
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  resid
## X-squared = 15.134, df = 23, p-value = 0.8897
Box.test(resid, lag=36, type = "Ljung-Box", fitdf=1)
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  resid
## X-squared = 29.215, df = 35, p-value = 0.743
Box.test(resid, lag=48, type = "Ljung-Box", fitdf=1)
## 
##  Box-Ljung test
## 
## data:  resid
## X-squared = 39.726, df = 47, p-value = 0.7652

From above plots and test it is clear thatresiduals are stationary. Now let us forecast for next 6 months

forecast(fit,h=6,level=95)
##          Point Forecast     Lo 95    Hi 95
## Feb 2019       1.313802 1.1289901 1.498614
## Mar 2019       1.351932 1.0389901 1.664873
## Apr 2019       1.377139 0.9541266 1.800152
## May 2019       1.416461 0.9024556 1.930466
## Jun 2019       1.446754 0.8596266 2.033880
## Jul 2019       1.460391 0.8154339 2.105348
fcast<-forecast(fit,h=6,level=95)
plot(fcast)
